column1: ,To determine when the next orbital period will begin starting from the time of perihelion, we need to add the length of one complete orbital period to the date of the most recent perihelion.
From the table, the date of the most recent perihelion is given as 2042-Sep-04.
The orbital period of Neptune is given as 164.8 years.
Adding 164.8 years to the perihelion date of 2042-Sep-04 gives us approximately the start of the next orbital period.
Since 164.8 years is very close to 165 years, we can approximate adding 165 years to 2042 to find the start of the next orbital period.
Therefore, the next orbital period will begin around the year 2207.

Now let's calculate the difference between these two dates:
- The ODI debut happened before the last Test, so we'll subtract the debut date from the last Test date.
- From 13 July 1974 to 13 July 1986 is exactly 12 years.
- Since his last Test was on 19 June 1986, it means he had one more year of Test cricket after his ODI debut.

3. Calculate the duration of the conflict up to 1975:
- From 1 November 1965 to 31 December 1965 is approximately 11 months.
- Adding full years from 1966 to 1974 gives us 9 years.
- Adding the partial year of 1975 up to the end of the year adds another full year.
Adding these together: 11 months (in 1965) + 9 full years (1966-1974) + 1 year (1975) = 10 years and 11 months.
Since the question asks for the number of years, we can round this down to 10 years.
